# Vercel Web Analytics Integration Report

## Summary
Successfully installed and configured Vercel Web Analytics for the GMIS Expo/React Native Web application.

## Changes Made

### 1. Package Installation
- Installed `@vercel/analytics` version 2.0.1 using npm
- Package added to dependencies in package.json
- Updated package-lock.json with new dependency tree

### 2. Analytics Integration
Modified: `app/_layout.tsx`
- Added import: `import { Analytics } from "@vercel/analytics/react"`
- Integrated `<Analytics />` component into the root layout
- Placed the Analytics component inside the ToastProvider to ensure it's properly rendered in the component tree

## Implementation Details

The Analytics component was added to the root layout (`app/_layout.tsx`) which is the entry point for the Expo Router application. This ensures:
- Analytics tracking is available across all routes in the application
- The component is initialized once when the app loads
- Web analytics will track page views and interactions when the app runs in web mode

### Framework-Specific Approach
- Used `@vercel/analytics/react` import as this is an Expo app with React Native Web support
- The Analytics component is web-only and will not affect native iOS/Android builds
- Compatible with the existing Expo Router setup

## Verification
- TypeScript compilation: ✓ Passed (no errors)
- Package installation: ✓ Successful
- Build compatibility: ✓ Verified

## Next Steps
Once deployed to Vercel:
1. Enable Web Analytics in the Vercel dashboard under Analytics settings
2. Deploy the application to Vercel
3. Analytics data will start appearing in the dashboard after users visit the site

## Notes
- The Analytics component is designed for web deployments and will automatically handle tracking
- No additional configuration is required in the code
- Analytics data is only collected when the app is deployed on Vercel's infrastructure
